7 years ago on my first IM 70.3 !

With over 23 70.3 events under my belt it’s really crazy to look back and see how time flies by and as I will be racing my 10th full IM this weekend in #IMWA 🇦🇺 

Not much has changed though, with the exception of a few things 😂:

1) I no longer run out of T2 with cycling gloves 😅
2) Shaved off a few pounds of weight and hair😂
3) Stopped wearing Mountain Bike helmets 🤣
4) Now I wear good looking trisuits 😅
5) Seems I no longer chase #Kona 🌺 slots thanks to @ironmantri 🤷🏻‍♂️🤦🏻‍♂️

It’s always good to look back at how you started and how far you’ve come leaving all jokes aside! One thing is for sure though, the passion and fire remain the same 🔥🦾

4 days to go 🚀 

#triathloncoach #endurancecoach #ironmancoach #ironmantraining #triathlontraining #ironmanworldchampionship

10th full IRONMAN in the books 🦾

I woke up feeling TERRIBLE on race morning but decided to give it a go anyways. I felt bad throughout the swim and the first half of the bike where I finally started to find my legs 🚀

What I’m most happy about is I was finally able to perform a decent 3:15 marathon on a full Ironman up to my capabilities. 

Unfortunately, I ended in the medical tent and today I got confirmation that I had COVID at the time of the race 🤦🏻‍♂️ It would have never crossed my head but now that explains a lot of things.

Time to rest up 🙌

#triathloncoach #endurancecoach #ironmancoach #ironmantraining #triathlontraining #imwa

“Philip Billikopf is the Co-Founder of Mauna Endurance a global endurance coaching company.  Yes that’s right we sat down here on the @koasports01 podcast with the enemy!

Hardly, we admire the story and can relate to many of the challenges Phil and Mauna have faced over the past few years.

8 IRONMAN and 70.3 World Championship finishes to his name a very handy AG’er and endurance coach.

Koa Sports and Mauna Endurance have been locked in battle all year in the IRONMAN TriClub World Championships sitting P1 and P2, who will take the title in 2022?”

We need more people like this in the sport of triathlon! Not because we are direct competitors it means we can’t share a beer, exchange knowledge & have a good time! 

In a world where most people are talking constant shit about each other, you know you can sit down head to head with your “enemy” when both of you are doing things the right way! 

Listen to the podcast in my link in bio! 🎤🎧

📸 @aprilgilliessportsphotography 

#triathloncoach #endurancecoach #ironmancoach #ironmantraining #triathlontraining #triathlonpodcast

It’s been a crazy week after the @ironmantri announcement that the men’s race will no longer take place in 2023 in Kona 🌺 

Even though I’m very disappointed about this, sometimes these type of situations generate big opportunities. 

This scenario will be give more women the chance to race on the big island next year. You might agree or not but I think it has been really unfair witnessing how some women athletes placing 2nd place don’t get a slot for the World Championship.

About 50% of my coached athletes are women and I have sat down to chat with the ones I believe have a good chance of qualifying next year! If you are a competitive athlete looking to qualify to Kona next year let’s chat!

After 2 off weeks with absolutely zero triathlon, lots of food & drinks, beach & family time, and complete physical + mental reset, I’m ready to start shaping the 2023 season ⛏️

This year I hit PRs in pretty much every distance and raced 3 World Championships, 3 full Ironmans, 3 70.3s and 1 marathon.

⏰70.3 PR: 4:16
⏰140.6 PR: 9:31
⏰Marathon PR: 2:48

Even though these are just numbers, the important trend is that they are faster each year. Triathlon is a sport that pays off hard work and discipline but results come in the long term.

My proudest PR this season is not any of these race times but the fact that I could finally run up to my potential in an Ironman Marathon. I ran a 3:15 marathon at Ironman Western Australia without knowing I had Covid. I feel I am barely scratching the surface of how fast I can run.

However, this result gives me the confidence to chase that goal next season. How did I obtain this result after years of failure?

I can definitely say I lack talent but the people who know me can tell how much work and dedication I put into this sport. 

Hard work needs to be paired with a solid coach that can look at everything from an outside perspective. Even though I’m a coach myself and have been coached by  some very well known coaches/professional athletes, this is something I was never able to achieve. 

In a coaching relationship, chemistry is key and your coach needs to understand your work, family and availability to be open to accommodate to your needs. If your coach isn’t open to suggestions or thinks they know it all, run away!

Thank you @czechchick15 for taking me onboard in the middle of the season, and helping me reach those goals that at moments seemed unreachable!

#notalent #allhardwork 
#runner #triathlete #offseason #triathloncoach #ironmancoach

But it's not just about the races and the medals. Triathlon has given me so much more than that. It has become my job and lifestyle, allowed me to explore the world, to immerse myself in different cultures, and to connect with amazing people from all walks of life. In the pasts two months I've been fortunate enough to travel through 15 countries in a motorhome, experiencing the beauty and diversity of Europe, all while pursuing my passion.

The road to this moment hasn't always been easy. There have been setbacks, challenges, and moments of doubt. But through it all, I've learned the power of perseverance and the importance of never giving up on your dreams. Each race, each training session, has been a stepping stone towards this moment, and I am ready to give it my all.

So, as I prepare to dive into the crystal-clear waters of Nice, I want to remind you all that anything is possible. No dream is too big, no goal is too far-fetched. It's all about believing in yourself, putting in the hard work, and embracing the journey.

Thank you to everyone who has supported me along the way - my family, friends, coaches, sponsors, athletes I coach and all @maunaendurance Team Members! I am forever grateful for your support and encouragement.

Now, it's time to shine. It's time to push my limits and leave it all out there!

Join me on this incredible journey as I chase my dreams and inspire others to do the same. Together, let's conquer the world, one race at a time! 🦾🌍

"Sometimes, things may not go your way, but the effort should be there every single night." - Michael Jordan

Today was a true test of resilience and determination. I knew it was going to be a challenging day, little did I know that it would turn out to be the toughest one yet, filled with valuable lessons.

During my race, at mile 40, my tire unexpectedly started leaking, turning out to have a massive gash. It was a setback that could have easily ended up in a DNF, but I refused to let it define my outcome. I spent over two hours tirelessly attempting to fix it, stopping at multiple aid stations to pump more air into my back wheel until someone provided me with a tourniquet.

I want to express my gratitude to my teammate @matt_garrett8 for stopping and ensuring I was ok! 

For the first time, I found myself in a real race against the bike cut off, and simply making it into T2 felt like a monumental victory. The support and messages I received from all of you, asking about what had happened is truly appreciated . I apologize if I couldn't respond to everyone individually, but please know that every single message meant a lot to me!

I am incredibly grateful to have crossed the finish line of another IMWC, and I am hopeful that the second part of this season will bring better outcomes for me. Let this be a reminder to all of us that even when things don't go as planned, our unwavering effort and determination can still lead us to success. Stay strong, keep pushing, and never give up on your dreams. 🦾🚀

Life has a way of reminding us to pause and take care of ourselves.

Following an intense race season that took me across many countries, coupled with the demands of growing a business, I had plans to come back and race in a late-season Ironman. However, upon returning from Europe, I faced a series of setbacks.

On Sunday, I was hospitalized and diagnosed with acute pneumonia. This forced me to prioritize my health and slow down. As we all understand, progress isn’t always a straight path, so I’m embracing this period of recovery, ensuring I regain my health before I resume my activities.

On a positive note, this break has provided me with an opportunity to concentrate on @maunaapparel and some exciting projects and new names we have lined up for the coming year. Stay tuned for some big announcements! 😉

Race Report: Ironman 70.3 Pucon 🏊🏻 🚴🏼 🏃🏻 

After 4 intense days at the expo with @maunaapparel, I was pumped up and ready for the race! The swim was challenging with choppy waters and low visibility, but I managed to have a decent swim considering the conditions. 💪

Onto the bike, I knew I had to push hard to catch up with the faster swimmers. I felt great and powered through, working together with a group led by my good friend @guille_garcia_89 and myself. They say this race is the most beautiful in the world, and I couldn’t agree more. However, it was also the race with the most drafting, with groups of 20-30 people sticking together. 

Unfortunately, the rain was very strong and there was some sections of terrible tarmac. I hit a pothole, tearing my tire open. It was a frustrating moment, as I knew I had a killer run in me. After 45 minutes of trying to fix the flat in the freezing rain, I made it to t2 and thought my day was over.

But then, I saw my friend and mentor @patojaca in triathlon, who had helped me in my very first race. In that moment, I realized that this race had a different purpose. Despite the setbacks, it became one of the most meaningful finishes I’ve ever experienced. Sometimes, it’s not about the result, but the journey itself. 

Key takeaways from this race:
1️⃣ @maunaapparel had an incredible presence on the course, with so many kits out there. The expo also went amazing and it was our best one yet!
2️⃣ I know I’m on the right track and feeling strong and fit. Time to get back to work 🚀
3️⃣ Congratulations to Mauna Pros @luciano_taccone and @elizabethbravoi for their solid second-place finish! 🥈
4️⃣ Sharing an amazing half marathon with a lifelong friend made this race truly special.

Onwards and upwards! 🚀🔥
